 ###### 
From cou.: 1 We explore the effects of line tension on the shape of two component elastic shells. Segregation between components with different elastic properties combined with the subtleties related to the spherical topology leads to a rich variety of shapes. They range from irregular polyhedra at weak segregation to Janus-like morphologies with spherical and buckled regions coexisting on the same shell for large values of the line tension. We use Monte Carlo simulations to map a detailed phase diagram as a function of the relative fraction of the two components, the ratio of their bending rigidities, and the strength of the line tension.
From Soup: 1 We explore the effects of line tension on the shape of two component elastic shells. Segregation between components with different elastic properties combined with the subtleties related to the spherical topology leads to a rich variety of shapes. They range from irregular polyhedra at weak segregation to Janus-like morphologies with spherical and buckled regions coexisting on the same shell for large values of the line tension. We use Monte Carlo simulations to map a detailed phase diagram as a function of the relative fraction of the two components, the ratio of their bending rigidities, and the strength of the line tension.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 Nature has developed ingenious ways to exploit shape for function, the cell being one of the best examples. Cell shape as well as the shapes of virtually all organelles are to a large extent determined by the membranes that surround them. Virtually all biological membranes are bilayers of lipid molecules with a large number of associated and embedded proteins.1Lipid molecules are held together by a non-covalent hydrophobic attraction between the nonpolar hydrocarbon chains. The bilayer is approximately 5 nm thick, but may span tens of nanometres to a few microns laterally, suggesting that it can be described as a thin sheet at length scales large compared to its thickness. Despite the high morphological complexity of biological membranes, a surprising amount of insight about their shape can be deduced from simple elastic models with only a handful of parameters. In a seminal work, Helfrich introduced2 a Hamiltonian that models the bending degrees of freedom as a quadratic function of the membrane curvatures. In this simplified mesoscopic description of a highly complex atomistic system, the membrane shape is taken to depend only on a few parameters such as the spontaneous curvature and the bending rigidity. The Helfrich model is particularly suitable for fluid membranes where lipid molecules are able to freely diffuse within the bilayer, thus resulting in a system that cannot sustain shear but shows resistance to bending.
From Soup: 2 Nature has developed ingenious ways to exploit shape for function, the cell being one of the best examples. Cell shape as well as the shapes of virtually all organelles are to a large extent determined by the membranes that surround them. Virtually all biological membranes are bilayers of lipid molecules with a large number of associated and embedded proteins . 1 Lipid molecules are held together by a non-covalent hydrophobic attraction between the nonpolar hydrocarbon chains. The bilayer is approximately 5 nm thick, but may span tens of nanometres to a few microns laterally, suggesting that it can be described as a thin sheet at length scales large compared to its thickness. Despite the high morphological complexity of biological membranes, a surprising amount of insight about their shape can be deduced from simple elastic models with only a handful of parameters. In a seminal work, Helfrich introduced 2 a Hamiltonian that models the bending degrees of freedom as a quadratic function of the membrane curvatures. In this simplified mesoscopic description of a highly complex atomistic system, the membrane shape is taken to depend only on a few parameters such as the spontaneous curvature and the bending rigidity. The Helfrich model is particularly suitable for fluid membranes where lipid molecules are able to freely diffuse within the bilayer, thus resulting in a system that cannot sustain shear but shows resistance to bending.
