From cou.: 3 Another class of such quasi-two-dimensional systems are tethered membranes, i.e., membranes with suppressed lateral diffusion of lipid molecules. Such systems arise in nature, such as the widely studied cytoskeleton of the red blood cells,3,4 or can be artificially synthesized by cross-polymerizing the hydrophobic tails of lipid molecules,5,6 or directing the coassembly of cationic and anionic amphiphiles.7,8 We note that the effects of electrostatic interactions on the vesicle shape are particularly subtle and can lead to faceting9 or even a collapse of the shells.10 A tethered membrane can sustain shear, which is characteristic of a solid phase. Consequently, in addition to bending modes, any description of tethered membranes also requires consideration of the in-plane phonon degrees of freedom. The phonon degrees of freedom couple to the Gaussian curvature and drastically increase the bending rigidity. This leads to a suppression of the crumpled phase at low temperatures.11 If the tethered membrane is bent into a spherical vesicle, the topology requires defects to be present,12i.e., there must be isolated sites with coordination higher or lower than the common six-fold coordination of the close-packed two-dimensional lattice. The exact number of the defects is related to the integral of the Gaussian curvature,13, where Nz is the number of sites with coordination z, dS is the area element, G() is the local Gaussian curvature at position , and the integral is calculated over the vesicle surface S. For a sphere of radius R, the Gaussian curvature does not depend on the position and is equal to 1/R2 at all locations on the surface. It is trivial to show that the integral on the right-hand side is equal to 4π for such a system, and therefore the total number of defects satisfies . Since the formation of topological defects is energetically costly, lowest energy configuration would be expected to have only five-fold and seven-fold coordinated defects. If we restrict the system by allowing only those two types of defects, then the total number of defects on a sphere satisfies the equation N5 − N7 = 12. It is reasonable to expect that the lowest energy configuration will have the minimal number of defects, suggesting that N5 = 12 and N7 = 0. We note that an instability toward the formation of grain boundaries can lead to lines of five- and seven-fold defect pairs termed “scars”, which can further reduce the elastic energy.14,15 However, here we assume that there is no such instability and throughout this paper consider only systems with 12 five-fold defects. To make a distinction between liquid and solid systems we will refer to tethered membrane vesicles as shells.
From Soup: 3 Another class of such quasi-two-dimensional systems are tethered membranes, i.e. , membranes with suppressed lateral diffusion of lipid molecules. Such systems arise in nature, such as the widely studied cytoskeleton of the red blood cells, 3,4 or can be artificially synthesized by cross-polymerizing the hydrophobic tails of lipid molecules, 5,6 or directing the coassembly of cationic and anionic amphiphiles . 7,8 We note that the effects of electrostatic interactions on the vesicle shape are particularly subtle and can lead to faceting 9 or even a collapse of the shells. 10 A tethered membrane can sustain shear, which is characteristic of a solid phase. Consequently, in addition to bending modes, any description of tethered membranes also requires consideration of the in-plane phonon degrees of freedom. The phonon degrees of freedom couple to the Gaussian curvature and drastically increase the bending rigidity. This leads to a suppression of the crumpled phase at low temperatures. 11 If the tethered membrane is bent into a spherical vesicle, the topology requires defects to be present, 12 i.e. , there must be isolated sites with coordination higher or lower than the common six-fold coordination of the close-packed two-dimensional lattice. The exact number of the defects is related to the integral of the Gaussian curvature, 13 , where N z is the number of sites with coordination z , dS is the area element, G ( ) is the local Gaussian curvature at position , and the integral is calculated over the vesicle surface S . For a sphere of radius R , the Gaussian curvature does not depend on the position and is equal to 1/ R 2 at all locations on the surface. It is trivial to show that the integral on the right-hand side is equal to 4π for such a system, and therefore the total number of defects satisfies . Since the formation of topological defects is energetically costly, lowest energy configuration would be expected to have only five-fold and seven-fold coordinated defects. If we restrict the system by allowing only those two types of defects, then the total number of defects on a sphere satisfies the equation N 5 − N 7 = 12. It is reasonable to expect that the lowest energy configuration will have the minimal number of defects, suggesting that N 5 = 12 and N 7 = 0. We note that an instability toward the formation of grain boundaries can lead to lines of five- and seven-fold defect pairs termed “scars”, which can further reduce the elastic energy. 14,15 However, here we assume that there is no such instability and throughout this paper consider only systems with 12 five-fold defects. To make a distinction between liquid and solid systems we will refer to tethered membrane vesicles as shells .
