From cou.: 4 The presence of the defects introduces a sizable strain into an elastic material. For a planar disk with a five-fold disclination in its center the elastic energy scales as the square of the disk radius R, E ≈ s2YR2/32π,16 where in analogy to electrostatics, s = 2π/6 is called the topological charge of the disclination and Y is the two-dimensional Young's modulus. If out-of-plane deformations are allowed, the disk buckles into a cone with the apex at the disclination core reducing the energy to E ≈ (π/3)κ log(R/Rb) + s2YRb2/32π,16 where Rb is the critical buckling radius and κ is the bending rigidity. From this expression for the conical deformation it is clear that the stretching energy now is a constant with respect to R, i.e., Es = s2YRb2/32π, at the expense of increasing the bending energy, which grows much slower with R, Eb ∝ log(R/Rb). For small R, it is energetically favorable to stretch and the disclination disk stays flat. As the radius increases, bending becomes less costly and the disk buckles into a cone. The transition occurs at ,16 where γc = 154 is a critical Föppl-von Kármán (FvK) number. The FvK number is defined as γ = YR2/κ and is a convenient dimensionless quantity (κ has units of energy and Y has units of energy per area) that determines the relative importance of stretching versus bending. For a thin elastic sheet with a two-dimensional Poisson's ratio ν it can be shown17 that , where h is the sheet thickness. As expected from the classical theory of elasticity,18 large thin elastic sheets are much easier to bend than stretch, consistent with large FvK numbers: γ → ∞ for h → 0.
From Soup: 4 The presence of the defects introduces a sizable strain into an elastic material. For a planar disk with a five-fold disclination in its center the elastic energy scales as the square of the disk radius R , E ≈ s 2 YR 2 /32π, 16 where in analogy to electrostatics, s = 2π/6 is called the topological charge of the disclination and Y is the two-dimensional Young's modulus. If out-of-plane deformations are allowed, the disk buckles into a cone with the apex at the disclination core reducing the energy to E ≈ (π/3) κ log( R / R b ) + s 2 YR b 2 /32π, 16 where R b is the critical buckling radius and κ is the bending rigidity. From this expression for the conical deformation it is clear that the stretching energy now is a constant with respect to R , i.e. , E s = s 2 YR b 2 /32π, at the expense of increasing the bending energy, which grows much slower with R , E b ∝ log( R / R b ). For small R , it is energetically favorable to stretch and the disclination disk stays flat. As the radius increases, bending becomes less costly and the disk buckles into a cone. The transition occurs at , 16 where γ c = 154 is a critical Föppl-von Kármán (FvK) number. The FvK number is defined as γ = YR 2 / κ and is a convenient dimensionless quantity ( κ has units of energy and Y has units of energy per area) that determines the relative importance of stretching versus bending. For a thin elastic sheet with a two-dimensional Poisson's ratio ν it can be shown 17 that , where h is the sheet thickness. As expected from the classical theory of elasticity, 18 large thin elastic sheets are much easier to bend than stretch, consistent with large FvK numbers: γ → ∞ for h → 0.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 Much like charges, same-sign disclination defects repel each other and tend to maximize their separation. On a sphere the most optimal configuration is an icosahedron with 12 disclinations located at its vertices. The positive Gaussian curvature partially screens the strain produced by the 12 five-fold disclinations and the elastic energy scales as E ≈ 0.604(s2YR2/4π).14 Analogous to the flat case, the shell can reduce its energy by buckling as the radius is increased. All 12 disclinations simultaneously act as seeds for conical deformation and the shell morphs from a sphere into an icosahedron.19,20 We note that the strong nonlinear nature of this buckling effect leads to very interesting scaling properties of the ridge deformations that form as a result.21,22
From Soup: 5 Much like charges, same-sign disclination defects repel each other and tend to maximize their separation. On a sphere the most optimal configuration is an icosahedron with 12 disclinations located at its vertices. The positive Gaussian curvature partially screens the strain produced by the 12 five-fold disclinations and the elastic energy scales as E ≈ 0.604( s 2 YR 2 /4π). 14 Analogous to the flat case, the shell can reduce its energy by buckling as the radius is increased. All 12 disclinations simultaneously act as seeds for conical deformation and the shell morphs from a sphere into an icosahedron. 19,20 We note that the strong nonlinear nature of this buckling effect leads to very interesting scaling properties of the ridge deformations that form as a result. 21,22
 ###### 
From cou.: 6 In summary, the presence of disclination defects on a shell is required by its spherical topology. The defects repel each other and adopt a configuration with icosahedral symmetry. For a sufficiently large shell radius, the residual elastic energy is reduced if all defects simultaneously buckle and the shell takes an icosahedral shape. Therefore, the symmetry of the buckled shell is directly dictated by the symmetry of the distribution of the topological defects. This is in essence the reason that small viruses tend to be spherical, while large viruses are icosahedral.19
From Soup: 6 In summary, the presence of disclination defects on a shell is required by its spherical topology. The defects repel each other and adopt a configuration with icosahedral symmetry. For a sufficiently large shell radius, the residual elastic energy is reduced if all defects simultaneously buckle and the shell takes an icosahedral shape. Therefore, the symmetry of the buckled shell is directly dictated by the symmetry of the distribution of the topological defects. This is in essence the reason that small viruses tend to be spherical, while large viruses are icosahedral. 19
 ###### 
From cou.: 7 So far this discussion has implicitly assumed that the shell is homogeneous, i.e., its elastic properties do not change with position. If this constraint is lifted and one introduces a soft, easily bent component, the shell can release some of the residual elastic energy by bending where that soft component resides. This removes the necessity for buckling seeded at disclinations and allows the formation of shapes with symmetries other than icosahedral. We have recently shown23 that even without an imposed mixing penalty between the soft and hard components (i.e., a line tension), the components segregate and form a wide variety of optimal shapes very different from the commonly observed icosahedron. The gallery of shapes is particularly rich with an assortment of regular and irregular polyhedral shapes if the two components are chosen such that the FvK number of one component is above the critical γc while for the other component it is below. Here we extend our recent model and focus on the effects of the line tension on the shell shape. We note that recent studies24,25 proposed a compelling description of the shapes observed by optical microscopy of giant multicomponent liquid vesicles.26,27
From Soup: 7 So far this discussion has implicitly assumed that the shell is homogeneous, i.e. , its elastic properties do not change with position. If this constraint is lifted and one introduces a soft, easily bent component, the shell can release some of the residual elastic energy by bending where that soft component resides. This removes the necessity for buckling seeded at disclinations and allows the formation of shapes with symmetries other than icosahedral. We have recently shown 23 that even without an imposed mixing penalty between the soft and hard components ( i.e. , a line tension), the components segregate and form a wide variety of optimal shapes very different from the commonly observed icosahedron. The gallery of shapes is particularly rich with an assortment of regular and irregular polyhedral shapes if the two components are chosen such that the FvK number of one component is above the critical γ c while for the other component it is below. Here we extend our recent model and focus on the effects of the line tension on the shell shape. We note that recent studies 24,25 proposed a compelling description of the shapes observed by optical microscopy of giant multicomponent liquid vesicles. 26,27
 ###### 
From cou.: 8 The paper is organized as follows. In Section 2 we briefly review the discrete elastic model for multicomponent shells and discuss details of the Monte Carlo simulations. In Section 3 we show galleries of shapes for different relative component fractions, ratios of the two bending rigidities, and line tension. We map a detailed phase diagram over a wide range of parameter values and discuss various relationships between elastic energy and line tension. Finally, in Section 4 we summarize the results and briefly discuss a number of open questions.
From Soup: 8 The paper is organized as follows. In Section 2 we briefly review the discrete elastic model for multicomponent shells and discuss details of the Monte Carlo simulations. In Section 3 we show galleries of shapes for different relative component fractions, ratios of the two bending rigidities, and line tension. We map a detailed phase diagram over a wide range of parameter values and discuss various relationships between elastic energy and line tension. Finally, in Section 4 we summarize the results and briefly discuss a number of open questions.
