From cou.: 9 We briefly review the continuum elastic theory for shells modified to include multiple elastic components and a line tension. The total energy is given as a sum of bending, stretching and line tension contributions, i.e., E = Eb + Es + Elt. The bending energy as introduced by Helfrich2 is given bywhere () is a position dependent bending rigidity, G() is a position-dependent Gaussian rigidity, is the mean curvature and is the Gaussian curvature with R1 and R2 being the principal radii of curvature, dS is the area element and H0 is the spontaneous curvature, which we set to zero for simplicity. The integral is calculated over the area of the entire surface. Note that = (s1, s2) is a three-dimensional position vector of a point on the surface parametrized in terms of the internal surface coordinates s1 and s2. The area element , with g being the determinant of the 2 × 2 metric tensor .28 We focus on a two component system with a binary distribution of bending and Gaussian rigidities, i.e., () = hard or () = soft and G() = Ghard or G() = Gsoft. In this case eqn (1) simplifies towhere the domains of integration Ds (Dh) correspond to regions occupied by the soft (hard) component. We note that the boundary between the two components is assumed to be smooth, but sufficiently narrow so as to not be distinguishable within the resolution of the discrete model discussed below. If the Gaussian rigidity G is position independent (i.e., Gsoft = Ghard ≡ G), then for closed surfaces with fixed topology (such that holes are not allowed to form) the Gauss-Bonnet theorem ensures that the integral is a constant, and thus the Gaussian curvature terms in eqn (2) do not influence the shape and can be dropped. However, for a multicomponent shell this is typically not the case, and G is different for each component. Thus, the expression for the bending energy depends on the (non-constant) integral of the Gaussian curvature. In Subsection 2.2 we discuss such a dependence for our model with two components.
