From cou.: 19 The optimal shell shape is obtained by minimizing the elastic energy functional. The Euler-Lagrange equations for this variational problem are a set of nonlinear partial differential equations,29 which cannot be solved analytically even for homogenous systems with simple geometries.18 Instead, we use a discrete model introduced by Seung and Nelson16 and find optimal shell shapes numerically by simulated annealing Monte Carlo simulations. The shell is represented as a triangular lattice constructed by a prescription introduced by Caspar and Klug to characterize spherical viruses.30 Such a lattice is specified by a pair of numbers, (p, q), which determines the total number of lattice sites N = 10T + 2, with the T-number defined by T = p2 + q2 + pq. As previously discussed, spherical topology requires at least 12 lattice sites to have the coordination number z = 5; all other lattice sites are six-coordinated. Those 12 pentavalent sites are located on the vertices of an inscribed icosahedron, consistent with the expected minimal energy configuration of 12 dislocations on a sphere.14 To get from one defect to another, one makes p steps along a row of nearest neighbors, turns 120°, and moves an additional q steps. It is worth noting that (p, 0) and (p, p) structures are nonchiral, while all lattices with p ≠ q are chiral. However, this fact does not seem to affect any of our results.
From Soup: 19 The optimal shell shape is obtained by minimizing the elastic energy functional. The Euler-Lagrange equations for this variational problem are a set of nonlinear partial differential equations, 29 which cannot be solved analytically even for homogenous systems with simple geometries. 18 Instead, we use a discrete model introduced by Seung and Nelson 16 and find optimal shell shapes numerically by simulated annealing Monte Carlo simulations. The shell is represented as a triangular lattice constructed by a prescription introduced by Caspar and Klug to characterize spherical viruses. 30 Such a lattice is specified by a pair of numbers, ( p , q ), which determines the total number of lattice sites N = 10 T + 2, with the T -number defined by T = p 2 + q 2 + pq . As previously discussed, spherical topology requires at least 12 lattice sites to have the coordination number z = 5; all other lattice sites are six-coordinated. Those 12 pentavalent sites are located on the vertices of an inscribed icosahedron, consistent with the expected minimal energy configuration of 12 dislocations on a sphere. 14 To get from one defect to another, one makes p steps along a row of nearest neighbors, turns 120°, and moves an additional q steps. It is worth noting that ( p , 0) and ( p , p ) structures are nonchiral, while all lattices with p ≠ q are chiral. However, this fact does not seem to affect any of our results.
