From Soup: 137 Our goal is to simultaneously optimize the shell shape as well as the positions and sizes of the component domains. Numerical minimization techniques are very powerful in finding optimal shapes of shells and are widely used to optimize homogenous systems. However, it is impossible to adapt such schemes to simultaneously find the optimal distribution of components. Thus, one would need to specify a guess for the initial positions of the two components and then optimize the shape only, which is difficult and impractical. Instead, we use the simulated annealing Monte Carlo method. Initially, the sites are assigned to have either type hard or soft at random to satisfy a desired component fraction f , defined as the number of the soft component sites divided by the total number of lattice sites. Then a series of simulated annealing Monte Carlo steps are performed to simultaneously optimize the shell shape and the domain size and distribution. A Monte Carlo move consists of two sequential steps: (i) A random displacement of a vertex is attempted, followed by (ii) an attempt of swapping types of a randomly chosen pair of lattice sites. In both steps, moves are accepted according to the Metropolis algorithm. The system is heated up to a high temperature and cooled down until an energy minimum is reached. Note that this is not the actual physical temperature, but a parameter that controls the level of stochasticity in the minimization procedure; it is referred to as the “temperature” for historic reasons. We compared exponential and linear cooling protocols and found that the linear cooling generally produced shapes with lower energies. With a Monte Carlo sweep defined as N attempted moves (where N is the number of lattice sites), each simulation consisted of five cooling and reheating cycles over a total of 10 6 Monte Carlo sweeps (2 × 10 5 sweeps per cooling cycle). For each run the lowest-energy configuration was recorded. A typical run took approximately 6 h on a single core of a quad-core Intel Xeon processor at 2.26 GHz.
 ###### 
From cou.: 138 Our goal is to simultaneously optimize the shell shape as well as the positions and sizes of the component domains. Numerical minimization techniques are very powerful in finding optimal shapes of shells and are widely used to optimize homogenous systems. However, it is impossible to adapt such schemes to simultaneously find the optimal distribution of components. Thus, one would need to specify a guess for the initial positions of the two components and then optimize the shape only, which is difficult and impractical. Instead, we use the simulated annealing Monte Carlo method. Initially, the sites are assigned to have either type hard or soft at random to satisfy a desired component fraction f, defined as the number of the soft component sites divided by the total number of lattice sites. Then a series of simulated annealing Monte Carlo steps are performed to simultaneously optimize the shell shape and the domain size and distribution. A Monte Carlo move consists of two sequential steps: (i) A random displacement of a vertex is attempted, followed by (ii) an attempt of swapping types of a randomly chosen pair of lattice sites. In both steps, moves are accepted according to the Metropolis algorithm. The system is heated up to a high temperature and cooled down until an energy minimum is reached. Note that this is not the actual physical temperature, but a parameter that controls the level of stochasticity in the minimization procedure; it is referred to as the “temperature” for historic reasons. We compared exponential and linear cooling protocols and found that the linear cooling generally produced shapes with lower energies. With a Monte Carlo sweep defined as N attempted moves (where N is the number of lattice sites), each simulation consisted of five cooling and reheating cycles over a total of 106 Monte Carlo sweeps (2 × 105 sweeps per cooling cycle). For each run the lowest-energy configuration was recorded. A typical run took approximately 6 h on a single core of a quad-core Intel Xeon processor at 2.26 GHz.
From Soup: 138 All simulations were performed using a ( p , q ) = (12, 3) lattice with N = 1892 sites and an initial radius R ≈ 11.5 a . Unlike in ref. 9 where it was necessary to construct a projection that produced a uniform distribution of sites on a sphere, this is not the case here as all initial distortions quickly relax due to elastic forces. Therefore, it is sufficient to use a simple gnomonic projection when projecting the constructed lattice sites onto a sphere.
 ###### 
From cou.: 139 All simulations were performed using a (p, q) = (12, 3) lattice with N = 1892 sites and an initial radius R ≈ 11.5a. Unlike in ref. 9 where it was necessary to construct a projection that produced a uniform distribution of sites on a sphere, this is not the case here as all initial distortions quickly relax due to elastic forces. Therefore, it is sufficient to use a simple gnomonic projection when projecting the constructed lattice sites onto a sphere.
From Soup: 139 We explore the shell shapes as a function of the fraction of the soft component f , ranging from 0.05 to 0.95; the relative strength of the bending rigidities κ soft / κ hard , ranging from 0.01 to 1.0; and the dimensionless line tension Γ/ κ hard between 2 × 10 −5 and 0.1. The bending rigidity of the hard component is kept fixed and chosen such that its FvK number is well below the buckling transition. The value of the bending rigidity of the soft component is varied across the transition. For simplicity, the spring constants of both components are kept constant and equal, ε hard = ε soft = 0.1 κ hard / a 2 .
 ###### 
From cou.: 140 We explore the shell shapes as a function of the fraction of the soft component f, ranging from 0.05 to 0.95; the relative strength of the bending rigidities κsoft/κhard, ranging from 0.01 to 1.0; and the dimensionless line tension Γ/κhard between 2 × 10−5 and 0.1. The bending rigidity of the hard component is kept fixed and chosen such that its FvK number is well below the buckling transition. The value of the bending rigidity of the soft component is varied across the transition. For simplicity, the spring constants of both components are kept constant and equal, εhard = εsoft = 0.1 κhard/a2.
From Soup: 140 In Fig. 1 we show the phase diagram as a function of the relative bending rigidity κ soft / κ hard and the dimensionless line tension Γ/ κ hard for five different soft component fractions f . We observe four distinct shape and domain patterns. Snapshots of typical shell shapes are shown in Fig. 2(a)–(c) .
 ###### 
From cou.: 141 In Fig. 1 we show the phase diagram as a function of the relative bending rigidity κsoft/κhard and the dimensionless line tension Γ/κhard for five different soft component fractions f. We observe four distinct shape and domain patterns. Snapshots of typical shell shapes are shown in Fig. 2(a)–(c).
From Soup: 141 For large line tension, or a relative bending rigidity close to one, we observe a full segregation. Two distinct domains are formed whose sizes depend on the fraction f . In this regime, the line tension dominates over the shell elasticity. The overall shell shape is determined by both components adjusting their shapes to accommodate the existence of two separate domains. For low f , the majority of the shell contains the hard component which prefers to be spherical. The soft component forms a cap that can either be smooth if its bending rigidity is large or can buckle at the disclination defects if its FvK number is above the buckling transition, which occurs below κ soft / κ hard ≲ 0.08. As the fraction f is increased, the soft domain grows and at f ≈ 0.4−0.6 we observe shells with unusual Janus-like shapes, with one side being a smooth curved spherical surface and the other being buckled. The level of roughness on the buckled side can be controlled by tuning the shell size or the relative bending rigidity. As the soft component fraction is increased above f ≳ 0.7 the hard component becomes the minority and forms a relatively flat, facet-like domain.
 ###### 
From cou.: 142 For large line tension, or a relative bending rigidity close to one, we observe a full segregation. Two distinct domains are formed whose sizes depend on the fraction f. In this regime, the line tension dominates over the shell elasticity. The overall shell shape is determined by both components adjusting their shapes to accommodate the existence of two separate domains. For low f, the majority of the shell contains the hard component which prefers to be spherical. The soft component forms a cap that can either be smooth if its bending rigidity is large or can buckle at the disclination defects if its FvK number is above the buckling transition, which occurs below κsoft/κhard ≲ 0.08. As the fraction f is increased, the soft domain grows and at f ≈ 0.4−0.6 we observe shells with unusual Janus-like shapes, with one side being a smooth curved spherical surface and the other being buckled. The level of roughness on the buckled side can be controlled by tuning the shell size or the relative bending rigidity. As the soft component fraction is increased above f ≳ 0.7 the hard component becomes the minority and forms a relatively flat, facet-like domain.
From Soup: 142 At lower line tensions, where the elastic energy becomes comparable to the energy penalty for component mixing , a very rich set of shapes arise. Particularly interesting are shapes for soft component fractions f ≈ 0.1−0.5 at relative bending rigidity κ soft / κ hard ≲ 0.2 and low to moderate line tension (star symbols in Fig. 1 ). In this parameter region, we observe a large assortment of polyhedral shapes. The hard component forms well-defined domains that are nearly flat. These flat facets are separated by regions of the soft component that is highly bent. The total number of facets as well as the width and the curvature of the soft regions is sensitive to the actual values of the parameters. For very low f , the soft component forms thin lines on the spherical surface, with slight bulges occurring along those lines. As the fraction of the soft component is increased, facets start to form when f > 0.1 because then the soft component can tessellate the shell surface. At low values of f there are only a few rather large hard component facets while the soft component occupies very thin (one lattice site wide) edges. Even at very low relative bending rigidities κ soft / κ hard the hard faces are slightly bent, as required by the fixed volume and the limited amount of stretching allowed, i.e. , a fully flat facet would lead to a considerable amount of stretching to accommodate the increase of the total surface area required to encompass the given volume. If the line tension is kept fixed and the amount of the soft component is increased, at first one observes a proliferation of the number of facets. The soft component edges are still very thin, but there is more of them, separating a larger number of small hard component facets. This is to be expected, since a large number of small facets can easily reduce the curvature without too much stretching. In addition, the dihedral angles between neighboring facets on a polyhedron with a large number of small facets are smaller than the dihedral angles on polyhedra with a few large facets, further reducing the bending energy at the soft edges. The proliferation of the number of hard component facets eventually stops as the amount of contact between the two components reaches a value where the line tension becomes important. At that point the width of the soft component edges starts to grow. The onset of the edge coarsening depends on the actual value of the line tension. Thus, for low line tension and soft component fraction, the shell will be a polyhedron with hard component facets and sharp bends on very thin soft component edges. As Γ/ κ hard and f are increased, the soft component edges coarsen and lead to much smoother bends between the polyhedron facets.
 ###### 
From cou.: 143 At lower line tensions, where the elastic energy becomes comparable to the energy penalty for component mixing, a very rich set of shapes arise. Particularly interesting are shapes for soft component fractions f ≈ 0.1−0.5 at relative bending rigidity κsoft/κhard ≲ 0.2 and low to moderate line tension (star symbols in Fig. 1). In this parameter region, we observe a large assortment of polyhedral shapes. The hard component forms well-defined domains that are nearly flat. These flat facets are separated by regions of the soft component that is highly bent. The total number of facets as well as the width and the curvature of the soft regions is sensitive to the actual values of the parameters. For very low f, the soft component forms thin lines on the spherical surface, with slight bulges occurring along those lines. As the fraction of the soft component is increased, facets start to form when f > 0.1 because then the soft component can tessellate the shell surface. At low values of f there are only a few rather large hard component facets while the soft component occupies very thin (one lattice site wide) edges. Even at very low relative bending rigidities κsoft/κhard the hard faces are slightly bent, as required by the fixed volume and the limited amount of stretching allowed, i.e., a fully flat facet would lead to a considerable amount of stretching to accommodate the increase of the total surface area required to encompass the given volume. If the line tension is kept fixed and the amount of the soft component is increased, at first one observes a proliferation of the number of facets. The soft component edges are still very thin, but there is more of them, separating a larger number of small hard component facets. This is to be expected, since a large number of small facets can easily reduce the curvature without too much stretching. In addition, the dihedral angles between neighboring facets on a polyhedron with a large number of small facets are smaller than the dihedral angles on polyhedra with a few large facets, further reducing the bending energy at the soft edges. The proliferation of the number of hard component facets eventually stops as the amount of contact between the two components reaches a value where the line tension becomes important. At that point the width of the soft component edges starts to grow. The onset of the edge coarsening depends on the actual value of the line tension. Thus, for low line tension and soft component fraction, the shell will be a polyhedron with hard component facets and sharp bends on very thin soft component edges. As Γ/κhard and f are increased, the soft component edges coarsen and lead to much smoother bends between the polyhedron facets.
From Soup: 143 It is important to note that the polyhedral shapes are irregular and very different from the icosahedral shape of the soft shell with 12 disclination defects. In our simulations, the connectivity of the shell lattice does not change and thus the polyhedral shapes still contain exactly 12 defects. However, it appears that the shape of the polyhedral shell is essentially not influenced by the presence of these defects, suggesting a qualitatively different buckling mechanism compared to the one discussed in ref. 16, 19 . Instead at the defects the buckling occurs at the soft component, lifting the requirement for the 12-fold icosahedral symmetry, but allowing for shells that are faceted, i.e. , irregular polyhedra.
 ###### 
From cou.: 144 It is important to note that the polyhedral shapes are irregular and very different from the icosahedral shape of the soft shell with 12 disclination defects. In our simulations, the connectivity of the shell lattice does not change and thus the polyhedral shapes still contain exactly 12 defects. However, it appears that the shape of the polyhedral shell is essentially not influenced by the presence of these defects, suggesting a qualitatively different buckling mechanism compared to the one discussed in ref. 16, 19. Instead at the defects the buckling occurs at the soft component, lifting the requirement for the 12-fold icosahedral symmetry, but allowing for shells that are faceted, i.e., irregular polyhedra.
From Soup: 144 While the line tension and the soft-component fraction control the size of the domains, the relative bending rigidity κ soft / κ hard controls the amount of bending allowed at the soft component. For very low κ soft / κ hard values, it is energetically inexpensive to bend the soft component and the shell has a very pronounced polyhedral shape with very sharp edges and nearly flat facets. As κ soft is increased, the softness of the edges reduces and it becomes harder to bend them. Consequently, the shell gradually recovers the spherical shape. This transition is not sharp but rather very smooth. At κ soft / κ hard ≳ 0.2 the shell is essentially spherical. In this region (triangle symbols in Fig. 1 ), the size and shape of the domains is determined by the line tension. For very low Γ/ κ hard there is a large number of small domains. As the line tension is increased, the domains coarsen until the full segregation is reached.
 ###### 
From cou.: 145 While the line tension and the soft-component fraction control the size of the domains, the relative bending rigidity κsoft/κhard controls the amount of bending allowed at the soft component. For very low κsoft/κhard values, it is energetically inexpensive to bend the soft component and the shell has a very pronounced polyhedral shape with very sharp edges and nearly flat facets. As κsoft is increased, the softness of the edges reduces and it becomes harder to bend them. Consequently, the shell gradually recovers the spherical shape. This transition is not sharp but rather very smooth. At κsoft/κhard ≳ 0.2 the shell is essentially spherical. In this region (triangle symbols in Fig. 1), the size and shape of the domains is determined by the line tension. For very low Γ/κhard there is a large number of small domains. As the line tension is increased, the domains coarsen until the full segregation is reached.
From Soup: 145 We note that the faceting into polyhedra requires the hard component to be the majority component. If the soft component is the majority component, facets will not form since that would require edges to contain the hard component. Bending at the hard-component edges would require a prohibitive amount of elastic energy. Instead, the hard component forms small platelets that are locally flat and embedded into the otherwise curved surrounding region occupied by the soft component. That is why we do not observe any polyhedral shapes for f ≳ 0.7 (two right-most panels in Fig. 1 ).
 ###### 
From cou.: 146 We note that the faceting into polyhedra requires the hard component to be the majority component. If the soft component is the majority component, facets will not form since that would require edges to contain the hard component. Bending at the hard-component edges would require a prohibitive amount of elastic energy. Instead, the hard component forms small platelets that are locally flat and embedded into the otherwise curved surrounding region occupied by the soft component. That is why we do not observe any polyhedral shapes for f ≳ 0.7 (two right-most panels in Fig. 1).
From Soup: 146 Finally, for large concentrations of the soft component and very low relative bending rigidity, κ soft / κ hard ≲ 0.02, the hard component is so scarce that it forms small platelets on an essentially soft icosahedral shell. The origin of this icosahedral shape comes solely from the buckling of the disclinations as discussed in ref. 19 and is very different for the component-driven buckling discussed above. This narrow region is indicated with solid circles in Fig. 1 .
 ###### 
From cou.: 147 Finally, for large concentrations of the soft component and very low relative bending rigidity, κsoft/κhard ≲ 0.02, the hard component is so scarce that it forms small platelets on an essentially soft icosahedral shell. The origin of this icosahedral shape comes solely from the buckling of the disclinations as discussed in ref. 19 and is very different for the component-driven buckling discussed above. This narrow region is indicated with solid circles in Fig. 1.
From Soup: 147 In Fig. 3 we take a cut parallel to the Γ/ κ hard − f plane and plot the phase diagram for a fixed relative bending rigidity, κ soft / κ hard = 0.03, for which the soft component is well above the buckling transition. Accompanying snapshots of the optimal shell shapes are shown in Fig. 4 . As expected, for a large line tension one observes full segregation and the shell is partly spherical and partly buckled at the disclination defects. For low to moderate line tension and soft component fraction f ≲ 0.7, we observe polyhedral shapes. The only exception is the region of very low fractions, f ≈ 0.05, where there is not enough soft component to surround a full facet and instead the soft component forms scar-like lines on the surface of the sphere. For a soft component fraction f ≳ 0.7, the polyhedra are not observed. The soft component is the majority component and it prefers to stay bent with hard component facets dispersed within it.
 ###### 
From cou.: 148 In Fig. 3 we take a cut parallel to the Γ/κhard − f plane and plot the phase diagram for a fixed relative bending rigidity, κsoft/κhard = 0.03, for which the soft component is well above the buckling transition. Accompanying snapshots of the optimal shell shapes are shown in Fig. 4. As expected, for a large line tension one observes full segregation and the shell is partly spherical and partly buckled at the disclination defects. For low to moderate line tension and soft component fraction f ≲ 0.7, we observe polyhedral shapes. The only exception is the region of very low fractions, f ≈ 0.05, where there is not enough soft component to surround a full facet and instead the soft component forms scar-like lines on the surface of the sphere. For a soft component fraction f ≳ 0.7, the polyhedra are not observed. The soft component is the majority component and it prefers to stay bent with hard component facets dispersed within it.
From Soup: 148 While the transition from a polyhedron to a sphere as κ soft / κ hard increases is smooth, we expect an abrupt jump between a polyhedral shape and a fully segregated structure as a function of Γ/ κ hard . This is because the number of hard component faces has to be an integer, and one cannot continuously transition from four facets (the minimum for a polyhedron) to the single hard component domain observed in the fully segregated regime.
 ###### 
From cou.: 149 While the transition from a polyhedron to a sphere as κsoft/κhard increases is smooth, we expect an abrupt jump between a polyhedral shape and a fully segregated structure as a function of Γ/κhard. This is because the number of hard component faces has to be an integer, and one cannot continuously transition from four facets (the minimum for a polyhedron) to the single hard component domain observed in the fully segregated regime.
From Soup: 149 In order to gain some insight into the interplay between elasticity and line tension, in Fig. 5 we plot the average relative size of a hard component domain as a function of the line tension Γ/ κ hard for a shell with the relative bending rigidity of κ soft / κ hard = 0.03. The average relative domain size is defined as the average number of lattice sites in the domain divided by the total number of hard component sites. Thus, a fully-segregated configuration has a relative domain size equal to one. For low line tension, the domains are small and their size only slightly increases with Γ/ κ hard . Once a critical value of Γ/ κ hard ≈ 0.08 is reached we observe a rapid coarsening of the domains and the components fully segregate. The onset of the domain coarsening appears to be insensitive to the fraction of the soft component, with the transition being somewhat smoother for a predominantly soft shell ( f = 0.9). In the inset of Fig. 5 we show the changes of the bending, stretching and line tension energies per lattice site as a function of the line tension for a shell with f = 0.5. Note that the changes in stretching and bending energies are always negative since we use the elastic energy of the initial spherical configuration with a random distribution of the components as our reference point, which is higher than the energy of the relaxed shell. This does not pose a problem as we always use the same reference configuration.
 ###### 
From cou.: 150 In order to gain some insight into the interplay between elasticity and line tension, in Fig. 5 we plot the average relative size of a hard component domain as a function of the line tension Γ/κhard for a shell with the relative bending rigidity of κsoft/κhard = 0.03. The average relative domain size is defined as the average number of lattice sites in the domain divided by the total number of hard component sites. Thus, a fully-segregated configuration has a relative domain size equal to one. For low line tension, the domains are small and their size only slightly increases with Γ/κhard. Once a critical value of Γ/κhard ≈ 0.08 is reached we observe a rapid coarsening of the domains and the components fully segregate. The onset of the domain coarsening appears to be insensitive to the fraction of the soft component, with the transition being somewhat smoother for a predominantly soft shell (f = 0.9). In the inset of Fig. 5 we show the changes of the bending, stretching and line tension energies per lattice site as a function of the line tension for a shell with f = 0.5. Note that the changes in stretching and bending energies are always negative since we use the elastic energy of the initial spherical configuration with a random distribution of the components as our reference point, which is higher than the energy of the relaxed shell. This does not pose a problem as we always use the same reference configuration.
From Soup: 150 First, we note that the stretching energy does not considerably change, with only a slight increase at the segregation transition. On the other hand, line tension and bending energy are major players in the transition. Initially, for low values of the line tension, the bending energy remains essentially constant, while the line tension energy increases. In this regime, the shell shape is fully determined by elasticity and the line tension energy even increases compared to the random initial configuration. At the transition point the line tension energy rapidly drops at the expense of a sizable jump in the bending energy. The components completely segregate and form two separate domains. Elasticity no longer dominates the total energy and the shell shape is determined by line tension. The flip of the sign of the line tension energy change from Γ/ κ hard ≈ 0.1 results for our particular choice of the random initial configuration.
 ###### 
From cou.: 151 First, we note that the stretching energy does not considerably change, with only a slight increase at the segregation transition. On the other hand, line tension and bending energy are major players in the transition. Initially, for low values of the line tension, the bending energy remains essentially constant, while the line tension energy increases. In this regime, the shell shape is fully determined by elasticity and the line tension energy even increases compared to the random initial configuration. At the transition point the line tension energy rapidly drops at the expense of a sizable jump in the bending energy. The components completely segregate and form two separate domains. Elasticity no longer dominates the total energy and the shell shape is determined by line tension. The flip of the sign of the line tension energy change from Γ/κhard ≈ 0.1 results for our particular choice of the random initial configuration.
From Soup: 151 We point out that despite its powerful ability to concomitantly optimize the shape and the domain distribution, the simulated annealing Monte Carlo minimization has drawbacks. Under a few general assumptions, it can be proven 37 that with a suitable cooling protocol over an infinite time the method will locate the global minimum. However, within practically feasible simulation times one often finds only a local minimum, especially if the energy barriers between the minima are large or a few local minima have similar energies. In our problem this is clearly the case for very low values of the line tension. For a shell with f = 0.5 and κ soft / κ hard = 1 it is trivial to show that the minimum energy configuration for arbitrary small line tension consists of two identical hemispheres, each fully occupied by a single component. Our simulations clearly do not find this configuration for very small line tension (see, e.g. , left bottom snapshot in Fig. 2(b) ). We attribute this to a very small difference in the line tension energies between different component configurations. As Γ/ κ hard is increased, we recover expected solutions (see, bottom row in Fig. 2(b) left to right).
 ###### 
From cou.: 152 We point out that despite its powerful ability to concomitantly optimize the shape and the domain distribution, the simulated annealing Monte Carlo minimization has drawbacks. Under a few general assumptions, it can be proven37 that with a suitable cooling protocol over an infinite time the method will locate the global minimum. However, within practically feasible simulation times one often finds only a local minimum, especially if the energy barriers between the minima are large or a few local minima have similar energies. In our problem this is clearly the case for very low values of the line tension. For a shell with f = 0.5 and κsoft/κhard = 1 it is trivial to show that the minimum energy configuration for arbitrary small line tension consists of two identical hemispheres, each fully occupied by a single component. Our simulations clearly do not find this configuration for very small line tension (see, e.g., left bottom snapshot in Fig. 2(b)). We attribute this to a very small difference in the line tension energies between different component configurations. As Γ/κhard is increased, we recover expected solutions (see, bottom row in Fig. 2(b) left to right).
From Soup: 152 Despite its limitations, we believe that the simulated annealing accurately finds at least typical shell shapes if not truly optimal shapes, especially in regions far from the transition lines. In the vicinity of a transition, one would have to be more careful in determining the actual optimal shape. However, we do not have enough resolution in the parameter values to accurately pinpoint the exact positions of these transitions.
 ###### 
From cou.: 153 Despite its limitations, we believe that the simulated annealing accurately finds at least typical shell shapes if not truly optimal shapes, especially in regions far from the transition lines. In the vicinity of a transition, one would have to be more careful in determining the actual optimal shape. However, we do not have enough resolution in the parameter values to accurately pinpoint the exact positions of these transitions.
From Soup: 153 We have used simulated annealing Monte Carlo simulations to determine optimal shapes and domain distributions of a two-component elastic shell over a wide range of inter-component line tensions, relative concentrations of the components, as well as relative bending rigidities. We found a rich gallery of shapes, including a number of polyhedral structures at moderate values of the line tension and the bending rigidity ratio. For large values of the line tension, we observed a complete segregation of the components into shells with two distinct sides, one predominantly spherical and the other buckled.
 ###### 
From cou.: 154 We have used simulated annealing Monte Carlo simulations to determine optimal shapes and domain distributions of a two-component elastic shell over a wide range of inter-component line tensions, relative concentrations of the components, as well as relative bending rigidities. We found a rich gallery of shapes, including a number of polyhedral structures at moderate values of the line tension and the bending rigidity ratio. For large values of the line tension, we observed a complete segregation of the components into shells with two distinct sides, one predominantly spherical and the other buckled.
From Soup: 154 We argue that the observed faceting is driven by a mechanism very different from the one responsible for the buckling of a sphere into an icosahedron at the 12 disclination defects. 19 For moderate values of the line tension the minority soft component forms lines which act as edges of a polyhedron. The hard component segregates into facets that are flattened and the majority of the curvature is concentrated at the soft edges.
 ###### 
From cou.: 155 We argue that the observed faceting is driven by a mechanism very different from the one responsible for the buckling of a sphere into an icosahedron at the 12 disclination defects.19 For moderate values of the line tension the minority soft component forms lines which act as edges of a polyhedron. The hard component segregates into facets that are flattened and the majority of the curvature is concentrated at the soft edges.
From Soup: 155 Interesting shapes are observed for very weak line tension, in particular for values significantly smaller than the line tension used in a recent study of the multicomponent liquid vesicles. 25 We believe this is due to the fact that even without the line tension, two elastic components on a shell naturally try to segregate, as we have recently reported. 23 Thus, even a very weak line tension is sufficient to drive the components to fully segregate.
 ###### 
From cou.: 156 Interesting shapes are observed for very weak line tension, in particular for values significantly smaller than the line tension used in a recent study of the multicomponent liquid vesicles.25 We believe this is due to the fact that even without the line tension, two elastic components on a shell naturally try to segregate, as we have recently reported.23 Thus, even a very weak line tension is sufficient to drive the components to fully segregate.
From Soup: 156 Our analysis shows that it is in principle possible to combine two materials with different elastic properties to construct a wide variety of shell shapes with potential applications in medical imaging, drug delivery, or composite material design. In addition, results of this study provide a plausible explanation for the shapes of cell organelles such as carboxysomes 38 or shapes obtained via coassembly of cationic and anionic amphiphiles . 7,8 This study complements and considerably extends our recent analysis 23 of shapes of the two-component shells in the absence of line tension.
 ###### 
From cou.: 157 Our analysis shows that it is in principle possible to combine two materials with different elastic properties to construct a wide variety of shell shapes with potential applications in medical imaging, drug delivery, or composite material design. In addition, results of this study provide a plausible explanation for the shapes of cell organelles such as carboxysomes38 or shapes obtained viacoassembly of cationic and anionic amphiphiles.7,8 This study complements and considerably extends our recent analysis23 of shapes of the two-component shells in the absence of line tension.
From Soup: 157 Our model assumes the presence of the 12 disclination defects originating from the construction of a crystal lattice on a sphere. However, our results suggest that the faceting into polyhedral shapes is not directly related to the defects, even thou their presence introduces strain to the shell. It would be interesting to investigate the extent to which the defect-induced strain influences the faceting. In addition, it would be useful to develop a simple analytical model that would provide some scaling arguments for the edge length and width as a function of the line tension and bending rigidity. Steps in this direction were recently made, 39,40 albeit for single component polyhedral shells, where a model based on the bending of ridges and vertices was used to compare elastic energies of various regular and irregular polyhedra.
 ###### 
From cou.: 158 Our model assumes the presence of the 12 disclination defects originating from the construction of a crystal lattice on a sphere. However, our results suggest that the faceting into polyhedral shapes is not directly related to the defects, even thou their presence introduces strain to the shell. It would be interesting to investigate the extent to which the defect-induced strain influences the faceting. In addition, it would be useful to develop a simple analytical model that would provide some scaling arguments for the edge length and width as a function of the line tension and bending rigidity. Steps in this direction were recently made,39,40 albeit for single component polyhedral shells, where a model based on the bending of ridges and vertices was used to compare elastic energies of various regular and irregular polyhedra.
From Soup: 158 Finally, we note that our analysis focuses only on the thermodynamic aspects of the problem, i.e. , we determine optimal shell shapes without addressing the important problem of the kinetics of their formation. For example, in multicomponent liquid bilayers the segregation of different lipid species occurs through a lateral diffusion of lipid molecules. In the case of tethered multicomponent shells, diffusion is suppressed and the components either organize themselves during the vesicle assembly or elastic heterogeneities are introduced externally by adsorption 41 or by changing local charge conditions in the case of ionic amphiphiles . 8 Although very interesting, a full treatment of the kinetics of the formation of structures reported in this study would require knowledge of the specific details of a relevant experimental system and necessitate a more sophisticated analysis than used here.
 ###### 
From cou.: 159 Finally, we note that our analysis focuses only on the thermodynamic aspects of the problem, i.e., we determine optimal shell shapes without addressing the important problem of the kinetics of their formation. For example, in multicomponent liquid bilayers the segregation of different lipid species occurs through a lateral diffusion of lipid molecules. In the case of tethered multicomponent shells, diffusion is suppressed and the components either organize themselves during the vesicle assembly or elastic heterogeneities are introduced externally by adsorption41 or by changing local charge conditions in the case of ionic amphiphiles.8 Although very interesting, a full treatment of the kinetics of the formation of structures reported in this study would require knowledge of the specific details of a relevant experimental system and necessitate a more sophisticated analysis than used here.
